   Robert and Chia, Nicholas and Chard, Kyle and Ross, Robert and
   Venkataraman, Shivaram},
Book-Group-Author = {ACM},
Title = {Exploring Distributed Vector Databases Performance on HPC Platforms: A
   Study with Qdrant},
Booktitle = {PROCEEDINGS OF 2025 WORKSHOPS OF THE INTERNATIONAL CONFERENCE ON HIGH
   PERFORMANCE COMPUTING, NETWORK, STORAGE, AND ANALYSIS, SC25 WORKSHOPS},
Year = {2025},
Pages = {575-581},
Note = {2025 Workshops of the International Conference for High Performance
   Computing Networking Storage and Analysis-SC-W, St. Louis, MO, NOV
   16-21, 2025},
Organization = {ACM Special Interest Group on High Performance Computing; IEEE Computer
   Society},
Abstract = {Vector databases have rapidly grown in popularity, enabling efficient
   similarity search over data such as text, images, and video. They now
   play a central role in modern AI workflows, aiding large language models
   by grounding model outputs in external literature through
   retrieval-augmented generation. Despite their importance, little is
   known about the performance characteristics of vector databases in
   high-performance computing (HPC) systems that drive large-scale science.
   This work presents an empirical study of distributed vector database
   performance on the Polaris supercomputer in the Argonne Leadership
   Computing Facility. We construct a realistic biological-text workload
   from BV-BRC and generate embeddings from the peS2o corpus using
   Qwen3-Embedding-4B. We select Qdrant to evaluate insertion, index
   construction, and query latency with up to 32 workers. Informed by
   practical lessons from our experience, this work takes a first step
   toward characterizing vector database performance on HPC platforms to
   guide future research and optimization.},
