Month = {MAY 1},
Abstract = {Large Language Models (LLMs) have fundamentally changed code engineering
   by automating code-related tasks, including code generation, completion,
   debugging, and optimization. General-purpose LLMs sometimes struggle
   with code-specific challenges, including syntax errors, suboptimal code
   efficiency, and security vulnerabilities, notwithstanding their success.
   Using specialized datasets, domain-adaptive training, and focused
   fine-tuning techniques, CSLLMs (Code-Specific Large Language Models)
   have emerged to solve these problems. Synthesizing present research on
   CSLLMs, this literature review investigates their architectures,
   training paradigms, motivating strategies, fine-tuning techniques,
   benchmark datasets, and evaluation approaches. To highlight their
   strengths, constraints, and useful applications, eminent models
   including Codex, CodeT5, StarCoder, and DeepSeekCoder are arranged and
   comparatively studied. Driven by methods including identifier-aware
   pretraining, retrieval-augmented learning, and execution-based
   evaluation, the results show that CSLLMs routinely outperform
   generalpurpose models in code accuracy, syntactic correctness, and
   execution reliability. Still, there are important obstacles, including
   ethical issues in code generation, computational complexity, and dataset
   biases. Our study emphasizes exciting research directions, supports
   hybrid architectures, strong execution-based evaluations, and ethical
   frameworks, and guides next developments in AI-assisted programming for
   both industry and academia.},
