   Hypertext and the Web; ACM Special Interest Group on Information
   Retrieval; Korea Tourism Organization; Seoul Metropolitan Government},
Abstract = {While Large Language Models have achieved remarkable success across a
   wide range of tasks, they suffer from hallucination, especially in
   scenarios requiring extensive background knowledge. A common strategy to
   address this shortcoming is to incorporate external knowledge, such as
   retrieval augmented generation. However, existing RAG methods mainly
   focus on text data, and overlook an important information: the
   connections between knowledge. In fields like scientific publishing,
   entities such as papers and authors form intricate graphs, where
   knowledge arises not only from individual texts but also from the
   relationships between them. Recognizing this, we propose Graph-MCTS, a
   framework designed to enhance LLM reasoning by leveraging graph
   structures. GraphMCTS employs Monte Carlo Tree Search (MCTS) to guide
   the model through a structured exploration of graph-based knowledge. We
   evaluate Graph-MCTS across multiple LLM architectures and find that it
   delivers consistent improvements over existing augmentation methods.
   These results underscore the value of structured, relational knowledge
   in strengthening the reasoning capabilities of LLMs. Code can be found
   in https://github.com/lihuiliullh/GraphMCTS},
