Note = {5th African Human-Computer Interaction Conference-AfriCHI, Cairo, EGYPT,
   NOV 04-08, 2025},
Organization = {Arab Academy for Science Technology \& Maritime Transport College of
   Computing and Information Technology - Heliopolis},
Abstract = {African culture did not remain behind on the continent; it traveled with
   its people, adapting and evolving across the diaspora. One example of
   this migratory knowledge is As. e. (also rendered Ashe, Ache, or Axe), a
   Yoruba term that carries both spiritual and social power. Rooted in
   cosmological understandings of divine authority and intentionality, As.
   e. appears across Afro-Caribbean religions, African American cultural
   production, and even digital activism. Yet despite its wide and enduring
   presence, terms like As. e. remain difficult for computational systems
   to parse. This case study explores the implications of As. e. for
   Human-Computer Interaction (HCI), focusing on how culturally layered
   terms can be better understood and integrated into AI systems. We
   present a layered glossary approach and a prototype annotation tool that
   supports contextual interpretation of As. e. within retrieval-augmented
   generation (RAG) workflows. Through corpus analysis, system design, and
   researcher reflection, we model an HCI practice that treats cultural
   retention not as noise, but as valuable data. Our work offers a pathway
   for building systems that engage African diasporic knowledge with the
   care, flexibility, and reverence it deserves.},
